    <text type="letter"> 
        <body>
            <pb xml:id="leaf001r" facs="loc_es.00334.jpg" type="recto"/>
            <opener> 
                <dateline>
                    <name type="place"><handShift rend="printed"/>Superintendent's Office.<ptr
                        target="loc.07233_n1"/><lb/>ASYLUM FOR THE INSANE<lb/>LONDON.<lb/>
                        ONTARIO<lb/>London, Ont.,</name><date when="1888-09-07" rend="right"
                            ><handShift rend="manuscript"/>7 Sept <handShift rend="printed"
                            />188<handShift rend="manuscript"/>8</date>
                </dateline>
            </opener>
            <p>"Same subject continued" glorious weather and all quiet here at Asylum. Annual Report
                will have to be written this month, not begun yet, meter<ptr target="loc.07230_n2"/> moving slowly, wedding to
                attend in Sarnia next week&#8212;a nephew of Mrs Bucke's (Fred. Kittermaster<ptr target="loc.07233_n2"/> a young and
                very promising lawyer) marrying a daughter of Mr Pardee<ptr target="n4274"
                />&#8212;will be a grand affair. You ought to see the melon patch in our garden
                here&#8212;hundreds of melons lying thick on the ground <pb xml:id="leaf001v"
                    facs="loc_es.00335.jpg" type="verso"/> Little Robbie has just come into the
                office&#8212;all the rest of the children go to school<ptr target="loc.07233_n3"/>&#8212;Robbie has got to be a
                great boy for horses&#8212;wants to be riding or driving all the time&#8212;can
                handle a quiet horse as well as any one&#8212;will be seven years old the coming
                Xmas.</p>
            <p>I suppose you have not yet read "Robert Elsmere" by Mrs Ward<ptr target="n4300"
                />&#8212;it is quite a book &#38; I believe has made quite a stir in England&#8212;I
                am just reading it&#8212;it is calculated to make the modern Britisher
                think&#8212;</p>
            <p/>
            <closer>
                <salute>Love to you</salute>
                <signed rend="right">RM Bucke</signed>
            </closer>
